e heretofore unexamined economic consequences. This cutting-edge, comparative volume, the third in the joint series offered by the National Bureau of Economic Research and the Japan Center for Economic Research, explores those consequences, drawing specific attention to four key areas: incentives for early retirement; savings, wealth, and asset allocation over the life cycle; health care and health care reform; and population projections. Given the undeniable global importance of the Japanese and U.S. economies, these innovative essays shed welcome new light on the complex correlations between aging and economic behavior. This insightful work not only deepens our understanding of the Japanese and American economic landscapes but, through careful examination of the comparative social and economic data, clarifies the complex relation between aging societies, public policies, and economic outcomes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aaging, retirement, japan, pension, saving, population, reform, healthcare, asset allocation, wealth, nonfiction, economics, employment, labor, workforce, household, investment portfolio, intergenerational transfer, wages, incentives, promotion, insurance plans, annuity, united kingdom, government, policy, social security, poverty.1 aAbe, Yukiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAsano, Seki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutler, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEichner, Matthew J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaruyama, Tetsuya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNakanishi, Satoshi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNakayama, Noriyoshi, 